<h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Two-Letter Words Complete Strategy</h1>
<p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6">Tactical mastery for every situation — not just memorisation, but application</p>

<p class="text-lg text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-8">Most players learn the 2-letter word list. Fewer players understand when and how to deploy them. Knowing that QI exists is one thing — knowing that placing it parallel to an existing word to form three scoring opportunities simultaneously is what separates casual players from club-level competitors.</p>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Parallel Play Scoring — The Hidden Power</h2>

<p>The single most valuable application of 2-letter words is parallel play. When you place a word alongside an existing word, every adjacent pair must form a valid 2-letter word. If they do, each pair scores independently.</p>

<div class="border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
  <p class="text-blue-300 font-semibold mb-2">Example: Parallel Play Scoring</p>
  <p class="text-gray-300">Existing word: C-A-T on row 7. You play G-O-D on row 8 directly below it.</p>
  <p class="text-gray-300 mt-2">This forms: CG (invalid!) — so this doesn't work. But play G-A-T below C-A-T? That forms: CG (no). Try H-A-D: forms CH, AA, TD — AA works but TD doesn't.</p>
  <p class="text-gray-300 mt-2">The key: you need every vertical pair to be a valid 2-letter word. This is why knowing ALL 127 valid 2-letter words matters.</p>
</div>

<p>A well-executed parallel play routinely scores 30-50 points because you're scoring your main word PLUS each 2-letter crossword simultaneously. With premium squares involved, a humble 3-letter word played parallel can outscore a 6-letter word played in isolation.</p>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">The Complete Tier List</h2>

<p>Not all 2-letter words are equal. Here's a tactical tier list based on frequency of use and scoring potential:</p>

